üëÜ ONLY connect your hardware wallet to MetaMask via "connect hardware wallet" functionso remember: DO NOT EVER ENTER YOUR HARDWARE WALLET SEED WORDS INTO YOUR PC IN UNENCRYPTED FORM. BEST NOT TO DO IT AT ALLyou're in the wild west & everyone is trying to steal your money ü§†

üëÜ ...but do not EVER take the private key generated from your hardware wallet and enter it into MetaMask on your computerif you do you've effectively turned your "cold" hardware wallet into a "hot" wallet negating the purpose of using one entirely

üëÜ one final point of clarification:when you install MetaMask it makes you create a new wallet with a new private key. save those words too and only use them for smaller amounts (this is a "hot wallet" with the private key stored on your computer)...

üëÜ the hardware wallet basically acts like a single-purpose mini-computerkeeping your seed words safe while still allowing you to sign transactions from that device without exposing your private key / seed words to other electronic devicesthat is the benefit of using one

üëÜ this is perhaps a subtle point for newcomers but an important oneeven if you lose or damage your hardware wallet you can still recover all of your assets provided you have access to your private key (in the form of the seed words you used to initialize the wallet)

when you set up a hardware wallet with a seed phrase (which you should NEVER enter into a non-wallet device)and you send assets to an address on ityour assets are not "stored on the hardware wallet"the hardware wallet just securely stores your private key for you

How much of your crypto wealth should be in NFTs?NFTs are some of the most volatile markets the world has ever seen this depends on your risk tolerancemy rule of thumb is to keep my eth/nft ratio more on the eth side as my NFTs moon i sell or buy more eth with fiat (14/16)

However blue chip NFTs (punks/apes/OG art) have consistently outperformed eth even though they also dip during these eth ralliesthis may also be the case with many 10k collectible projects but we simply don't know yet as this is all just so new we're still learning (13/16)

When you buy NFTs you are betting they will outperform eththis is a concept many still struggle with I'm not saying you need to be bearish on eth to buy NFTs you just have to choose wisely if you're an eth bull which i think we all areas eth moons NFTs lose value (12/16)

How long should you hold before selling?This is a bad way of thinking about it.  You want to hold NFTs until they make you huge gains remember most of these collections will go to zeroBuy a little of each collection you want to be in and just hold till they 10x (11/16)

You really want to stay liquid in a new collection and it will be easier to sell for a profit (or breakeven) if you are holding floorsrares are more illiquid and I've always seen more ROI on collection floors than trait floors anywaybuy a rare for pfp not to flip (10/16)

If you have no experience with a collection don't buy raresyou'll be surprised how quick some of the ugliest looking NFTs in a collection get snapped up at floor (remember buyers are mostly flippers)many projects even include negative traits just to improve liquidity (9/16)

OK so lets say we have a great dev team a vibrant community and the metrics are looking good how do I know which to get? there are literally 10K choiceswell not really.  there are only as many choices are there are listings and you'll want to stay close to the floor (8/16) https://t.co/KKaHD609oT

Just don't put too much weight into this metric before researching further it's pretty easy to game by just splitting up where whales store their NFTs (Apes aren't doing this fyi)Each holder is a potential active community member and advocate for the project (7/16)

Unique Holder # is the most important metric but it's easily gamedYou can also see this in etherscan for any ERC-721 NFT project again Bored Apes wins against all other projects herethe thought is that no one wants to sell their last NFT from a project doing well (6/00) https://t.co/1fIpSYmqjm

The way whales list NFTs matters watch the biggest walletsif whales start dumping (listing at or below floor) prices will certain fall but responsible whale selling (listing very high without sell walls) is positive for an NFT projecttake note of their price targets (5/16)

Without a strong community any project is doomed this is why it's impossible to predict whether a project will succeed or not before minting the magic either happens or it doesn't The community is the tip of the spear the whales holding the most are just investors (4/16)

When you buy into an NFT project you are placing a bet on the community and dev team of that projectThis is why it's critical to spend some time in an NFT project's discord before making purchasing decisionsYou want to make sure there is a positive vibe before buying (3/00) https://t.co/HHDUU59xhn

You can see a list of holders for any ERC-721 NFT project by looking at the contract in etherscan and clicking on the "Holders" tabIt's best if you don't see too many in any one wallet as top holders will eventually exit and effect pricesthe BAYC distribution is best (2/16) https://t.co/4aXVfspWYw

And a really important note: the blatantly racist tactics of the defense did not work on a nearly all-white jury. The defense chose moral violence; the jury chose to follow the law. The prosecutor in this case should receive awards.

A well argued case by a really good prosecutor plus crimes that were clear as day and I cannot stress enough how important the message this jury has sent is. They have nullified an unjust and now repealed pro-lynching law. And they have restored at least some faith in justice.
William Roddy Bryan not guilty on two murder and one assault counts but guilty on everything else.
Greg McMichael guilty on all but one count.
Travis McMichael has been found guilty on all counts in the murder of Ahmaud Arbery. All counts down the line.

Guard your peace friends as we await this verdict in the McMichaels-Bryan trial. A fundamental question of whether Black people are truly free in this country or subject to the rule of any random armed white men is on the line. But deep breaths. #AhmaudArbery

He also claims he thinks a Black person in his position would have achieved the same legal outcome and resources. Banfield pushes back on that but he stays on message: that the entire case was merely about the right of self-defense with no larger implications or meaning.

Rittenhouse also talks about firing his initial lawyers Lin Wood and John Pierce calling Wood "insane" citing "Q-anon stuff" saying they tried to take back the $2 million they raised for him just as the case ended and revealing  it was Pierce who set up the Proud Boyz meetup.

If you know anyone who's been in combat you know that taking a life leaves a person with profound and deep regret even if they believe they had to do it. Yet Banfield also strikes out when she asks if Rittenhouse has any feelings of empathy for the families of the dead men.

Lately I've seen people ask why the US numbers don't look more like the UK which had a surge in cases recently but comparatively few deaths. But US states that have vaccination rates ~similar to the UK actually have fewer deaths than the UK though the numbers lag & may rise.

Seeing a bigger gap in deaths than cases is exactly what you'd expect given how the vaccines work under Delta (pretty good against cases but VERY good against severe outcomes) but still interesting to see it in the data.

Over the past week the 10 least vaccinated states are averaging 3.0x per cases per capita than the 10 most vaccinated states 4.3x more hospitalizations per capita and 6.5x more deaths per capita.https://t.co/i8ElZQJZ5p

IDK but I think a point that could be emphasized more in public health messaging (given how little testing the US is doing) is simply to encourage vaccinated people to get tested when they feel sick and stay home until they get a negative result.

This is a good thread and makes a key point. If you *randomly* sample people vaccinated folks *do* seem to have lower viral loads. Otherwise you're getting a sample of people who self-select to be tested usually because they feel sick. https://t.co/Yi9FpbdzAx

OTOH a higher percentage of breakthrough cases have few/no symptoms so maybe people wouldn't seek out testing for those.Still the states with high vax uptake also tend to be doing more testing. E.g. MA has about 2x as much testing per capita as MO despite much less COVID.

One useful piece of info would be how often people are getting tested by vaccination status. If you don't trust the medical system enough to be vaccinated you're probably not super inclined to get tested either.

Can you do better by also accounting for other stuff like gender pre-existing conditions and access to health care? Sure. But age is very very very important in determining COVID fatality rates and looking at age-based survival estimates is surely useful as a first pass.

Not sure which "experts" they're talking to but I doubt many would support this claim. You can certainly look at national statistics for your age group to get a reasonable benchmark for your chances of surviving COVID. https://t.co/yqxJCf9PuH
A lot of experts seem to think the NYT's recent story on long COVID in children was irresponsible. https://t.co/xhRZeI9xn9

Until recently the US was only doing about 1/3 as much testing as at our previous peak in the winter. It's since increased a bit but only to more like 1/2. You need to account for that when making inferences about death rates hospitalization rates etc.

I'm not as optimistic as this re: the US peak but still an Interesting thread. A year-and-a-half into this thing and a lot of people still haven't figured out that you don't know much about COVID spread until you account for the amount of testing. https://t.co/b3oxNQ7IDM

Hot Potato (2)These are some that might be frauds copies and things that go to 0 hours after launch. It's happened before many times.Simply use the same thesis as buying DOGE or SHIBA and apply it to NFTs.

Hot Potato (1)This is one that most will not like. Because it's a definition of others that are NGMI being taken "advantage" of if you want to put it the worst way possible.Buying NFTs that I do not believe in long-term and hardly short-term.

Long Term (3)But my list is quite limited. 99% of NFTs right now are inevitably going to be irrelevant. You should spend time to understand what you would put in your basket long-term and I choose some of these because I am overall bullish on NFTs.https://t.co/54vXcYQkdj
Long Term (2)BAYC fits into this category and is a reason why I will hold some of these for a long time to come. Another would be Treeverse plots + Nftrees (I am the founder).

Long Term (1)This is one strategy I've recently began to follow. Should be self-explanatory. Investments that I believe will be valuable long-term (3-5 years) and am happy to not think about short term volatility.

Short Term (5)This was when I started NFT trading I never held one long-term as it was never a strategy that interested me. Now that would be worth millions.And other short-term flips I've bought have been at the top. I'm still holding some which transition into long-term.

Short Term (4)This is one of my profitable (in small timeframes) but also one that can make you miss potential unrealised games (like every investment!). I bought around a dozen CryptoPunks at around $1000 - $2000. I sold all of them for a small gain of 5% - 10%.

Short Term (3)Cryptocurrencies started to stabilise after a week of high volatility. A lot of social media hype around these monkey JPEGs after a few events like NFT NYC. It seemed perfect.Short term flips are profitable if you know what you are looking for.

Short Term (2)My most recent one that I would put in this category is this Bored Ape I bought. I am incredibly bullish on the future of Apes (and I own a few that I do not plan on selling).But in this case BAYC was stabilizing at low levels for 1-2 months. https://t.co/yw91HygVYr

Short Term (1)The investments that I put in the short term category can be put into the long-term one too. When I say short term I mean that it's a play for me to quick flip generally before hype moments (e.g - announcements).

Now again when you are rich - plan to stay rich.The NFT market will mint many multi-millionaires for decades to come. And it will become a massive market. But like every market you will have losers on the other side. Remember that.

Participate in markets that you (or others) believe in long-term. Or be ready to exit if don't have belief in projects long-term.You can do exceptionally well with short-term gains but if you don't realise them you never did well.
Content is important. Providing content gives you a community. And community management is important.Having a community will give you many opportunities (and connections).
Don't be euphoric and quit your job after one NFT flip that makes you $10K. Consistency is key. One good flip doesn't mean the next 5 will be good.

The NFT market is a niche in the Crypto market. Movements in the Crypto market can directly impact the NFT market.Try to understand as much as you can about the sector of the market you are in blockchain games can be affected by traditional gaming news.

It can be mutually beneficial to help out others. Chances are they'll feel more inclined to help you when they can.Sharing a project that benefits them now can lead to you being shared a project that benefits you later.
Being a genius in one field (NFT trading) won't make you a genius in another (Crypto trading).After you get rich plan to stay rich.

In a space with so much opportunity people will prioritise taking advantage of others' visions for financial benefit.Don't fall for fake roadmaps.Don't fall for scammers.Don't fall for "experts who will teach you".Always take things with a grain of salt.

As always:More risk can lead to more reward.Projects at a higher valuation are typically safer than projects at lower valuations due to demand.And demand is due to historical performance.But one will bring you higher ROI in shorter timeframes.

When you sell buy or mint. You are still exchanging time for money.This can get you rich but it won't make you wealthy.Wealth is earning while you sleep. Most NFTs won't make you wealthy but you can still traditionally own equity of NFT companies to become wealthy.

Entering the NFT market is entering an illiquid market. Successful projects often have more liquidity but still don't confuse floor with "price I can sell at".And don't confuse "last sold" for the price YOU can sell at.
NFTs allow you to publicly "gain exposure" to brands founders or individuals. In a decentralised manner. Even if you are anonymous or pseudonymous.Take advantage of this. Leverage your identity.
The value of current NFTs are mainly due to community and culture.Understand community and culture.Participate in community and culture.Or do both.But remember:Understanding ‚â† Participating
Time in the market is better than trying to time the market. Learn from others.Understand how late you may be to one project so you can be early to the next.(CryptoPunks... Bored Ape Yacht Club... ?)

Choose a role and adapt. A builder investor creator or developer.Most people get rich through owning assets that later appreciate in value. And creating assets that appreciate in value.The assets you pick are often determined through the role you plan to play.

11/ TL;DR:Their is beauty in Web3 PFP projects already and demand is evident. Sustainability of these aren't certain if demand decreases best way to have continuous demand is becoming a brand. As much exposure to that project as you can digitally and physically.

10/ Projects like Punks aren't really an "avatar" project and weren't designed by LarvaLabs to be like them. They are more collectibles and don't really need to be a brand. Their brand is the collectible aspect of them.

9/ It's like buying a print of an artists' work from a site. Or buying straight from an artist.Avatar projects should become brands.This is the best way to increase demand benefit holders and have a longer-lasting future to them.

8/ If you don't (and I don't) it's good.More exposure to the project. More exposure to the artworks. Buildings clothing accessories digital stuff representing Timeless. And it doesn't stop the owner who owns the token that represents that image from monetizing.

7/ When we release Timeless it will be public domain. This means that anyone can use any of the avatars and commercially benefit from it.Is this bad?If you think the right-click and save argument makes a piece lose value then yes it's bad.

6/ Traditional world: Nike logo represents the Nike brand. Consumers buy anything associated with Nike.New world: BAYC logo & all BAYC avatars represent the BAYC brand. Consumers buy anything associated with BAYC.There are ways this can still be improved. But it's a start.

5/ "Community is empowered through demand"To touch more on this point. This is what it all comes down to imo. For a project to last long there needs to be more demand coming in.How do you do this?Simple. These avatar projects become brand(s).

4/ As said in the second tweet look at it from the culture perspective.Who are the people involved in the project? What is the project represented by?Culture is community. Community is empowered through demand."Wow he is part of the BAYC movement!"

3/ I know of many people skeptical about avatar projects. And it makes sense when you look at it from the general POV. People paying tens of thousands to represent themselves with a JPEG on Twitter.However the deeper you go the more you understand where value arises from.

2/ Avatar projects have definitely been the biggest thing in the NFT space in the last 3 months. BAYC Cool Cats Mekas. To many of us including myself it allowed us to look at NFTs from another perspective.The culture perspective. Community.

The biggest trend over 15 years of Reddit meetups was is always be surprised by something new - a new subreddit or meeting someone I knew online but IRL - now it's more than just about the satisfaction building community brings but what ownership does for all incentives

And the same effect I had at hundreds of Reddit meetups all over the world is happening all over NFT meetups I goto now - except the creators and the curators and the earliest adopters are rewarded for real. No middlemen.

Community took a decade to become a buzzword but now that everyone believe strangers can do amazing things together it's supercharged by ownership.... Earnings.... I designed some silly awards like "best comment or the day" or "n-year clubs" or karma points -- this is real.

That moment I knew Reddit might work - 2005 - that feeling of "Oh shit they're making their own communities and posting every day and I don't have to mod them or even post content to make them work" -- this is the start of something 100x bigger

I had a pretty well known VC ask me for #NFT advice this week and I told him - just do the work spend the time take time to understand community because this is the very start of the most important trend you're potentially going to miss but currently still early for.

Just when I thought I was starting to understand #NFT Community - I get my mind blown in Austin TX ü§Ø there are levels to this and it's like @reddit 3.0 for real and we just let users create their own reddit's (circa 2005)
